<tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>8992</anchor> <rss>jms-0045.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-0045</addr>  <route>jms-0045.xml</route> <date><year>2022</year> <month>12</month> <day>26</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Polarized object</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>An object <tex>A</tex> in a deductive system is called <em>polarized</em> when it is either <link href="jms-004B.xml" type="local" title="Positive or negative">positive or negative</link>.</p></mainmatter> <backmatter><contributions/> <context><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>8993</anchor> <rss>jms-004E.rss.xml</rss>  <addr>jms-004E</addr>  <route>jms-004E.xml</route> <date><year>2022</year> <month>12</month> <day>26</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Polarization, preduploids, and duploids</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" root="false"><frontmatter><trail><crumb>1</crumb></trail> <anchor>8994</anchor> <rss>jms-0045.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-0045</addr>  <route>jms-0045.xml</route> <date><year>2022</year> <month>12</month> <day>26</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Polarized object</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>An object <tex>A</tex> in a deductive system is called <em>polarized</em> when it is either <link href="jms-004B.xml" type="local" title="Positive or negative">positive or negative</link>.</p></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" root="false"><frontmatter><trail><crumb>2</crumb></trail> <anchor>8995</anchor> <rss>jms-004F.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-004F</addr>  <route>jms-004F.xml</route> <date><year>2022</year> <month>12</month> <day>26</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Preduploid</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>A deductive system <tex>\mathcal{D}</tex> is called a <em>preduploid</em> when every object <tex>A \in \mathcal{D}</tex> is <link href="jms-0045.xml" type="local" title="Polarized">polarized</link>.</p></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" root="false"><frontmatter><trail><crumb>3</crumb></trail> <anchor>8996</anchor> <rss>jms-0050.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-0050</addr>  <route>jms-0050.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>4</month> <day>15</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Duploid</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>A <link href="jms-004F.xml" type="local" title="Preduploid">preduploid</link> <tex>\mathcal{D}</tex> is called a <em>duploid</em> when it satisfies the following properties:</p><ol>  <li>the preduploid <tex>\mathcal{D}</tex> is <link href="jms-004T.xml" type="local" title="Univalent">univalent</link>;</li>  <li>every <link href="jms-004B.xml" type="local" title="Positive">positive</link> object of <tex>\mathcal{D}</tex> <link href="jms-004X.xml" type="local" title="Has an upshift">has an upshift</link>;</li>  <li>every <link href="jms-004B.xml" type="local" title="Negative">negative</link> object of <tex>\mathcal{D}</tex> <link href="jms-004Z.xml" type="local" title="Has a downshift">has a downshift</link>.</li></ol></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" root="false"><frontmatter><trail><crumb>4</crumb></trail> <anchor>8997</anchor> <rss>jms-0051.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Observation</taxon> <addr>jms-0051</addr>  <route>jms-0051.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>4</month> <day>15</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>An alternative definition of duploids</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Equivalently, we can define a <link href="jms-0050.xml" type="local" title="Duploid">duploid</link> to be a <link href="jms-004T.xml" type="local" title="Univalent">univalent</link> <link href="jms-004F.xml" type="local" title="Preduploid">preduploid</link> such that every object is <em>merely equipped with</em> both an <link href="jms-004M.xml" type="local" title="Upshift">upshift</link> and a <link href="jms-004P.xml" type="local" title="Downshift">downshift</link>.</p><p>To see that the <link href="jms-0050.xml" type="local" title="Main definition">main definition</link> implies our alternative definition, let <tex>A</tex> be an object of the preduploid; because we are proving that <tex>A</tex> is <em>merely equipped with</em> both an <link href="jms-004M.xml" type="local" title="Upshift">upshift</link> and a <link href="jms-004P.xml" type="local" title="Downshift">downshift</link>, we may proceed by cases on the <link href="jms-0045.xml" type="local" title="Polarization">polarization</link> of <tex>A</tex>.</p><ol>  <li>If <tex>A</tex> is <link href="jms-004B.xml" type="local" title="Positive">positive</link>, we choose the identity map <tex>A \vdash  A</tex> for the downshift and we use our assumption to deduce that <tex>A</tex> has an upshift.</li>  <li>If <tex>A</tex> is <link href="jms-004B.xml" type="local" title="Negative">negative</link>, we choose the identity map <tex>A \vdash  A</tex> for the upshift and we use our assumption to deduce that <tex>A</tex> has a downshift.</li></ol>  <block open="open"><headline><b>Proof</b>.</headline>   <p>Conversely, assume that every object is merely equipped with both an upshift and a downshift. That a positive object <tex>P</tex> has an upshift <link href="jms-004X.xml" type="local" title="Is a proposition">is a proposition</link>, so we can use our assumption that <tex>P</tex> <em>merely</em> has an upshift. That a negative object <tex>N</tex> has a downshift <link href="jms-004Z.xml" type="local" title="Is likewise a proposition">is likewise a proposition</link>, so we can use our assumption that <tex>N</tex> <em>merely</em> has a downshift.</p></block></mainmatter> </tree></mainmatter> </tree></context> <related><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>8998</anchor> <rss>jms-004B.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-004B</addr>  <route>jms-004B.xml</route> <date><year>2022</year> <month>12</month> <day>26</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Positive and negative objects</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>An object <tex>B</tex> in a <link href="jms-0048.xml" type="local" title="Deductive system">deductive system</link> <tex>\mathcal{D}</tex> is called <em>positive</em> when every map <tex>B \vdash  C</tex> is <link href="jms-004A.xml" type="local" title="Linear">linear</link>; it is called <em>negative</em> when every map <tex>A \vdash  B</tex> is <link href="jms-004A.xml" type="local" title="Thunkable">thunkable</link>.</p></mainmatter> </tree></related> <backlinks><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>8999</anchor> <rss>jms-0051.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Observation</taxon> <addr>jms-0051</addr>  <route>jms-0051.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>4</month> <day>15</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>An alternative definition of duploids</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Equivalently, we can define a <link href="jms-0050.xml" type="local" title="Duploid">duploid</link> to be a <link href="jms-004T.xml" type="local" title="Univalent">univalent</link> <link href="jms-004F.xml" type="local" title="Preduploid">preduploid</link> such that every object is <em>merely equipped with</em> both an <link href="jms-004M.xml" type="local" title="Upshift">upshift</link> and a <link href="jms-004P.xml" type="local" title="Downshift">downshift</link>.</p><p>To see that the <link href="jms-0050.xml" type="local" title="Main definition">main definition</link> implies our alternative definition, let <tex>A</tex> be an object of the preduploid; because we are proving that <tex>A</tex> is <em>merely equipped with</em> both an <link href="jms-004M.xml" type="local" title="Upshift">upshift</link> and a <link href="jms-004P.xml" type="local" title="Downshift">downshift</link>, we may proceed by cases on the <link href="jms-0045.xml" type="local" title="Polarization">polarization</link> of <tex>A</tex>.</p><ol>  <li>If <tex>A</tex> is <link href="jms-004B.xml" type="local" title="Positive">positive</link>, we choose the identity map <tex>A \vdash  A</tex> for the downshift and we use our assumption to deduce that <tex>A</tex> has an upshift.</li>  <li>If <tex>A</tex> is <link href="jms-004B.xml" type="local" title="Negative">negative</link>, we choose the identity map <tex>A \vdash  A</tex> for the upshift and we use our assumption to deduce that <tex>A</tex> has a downshift.</li></ol>  <block open="open"><headline><b>Proof</b>.</headline>   <p>Conversely, assume that every object is merely equipped with both an upshift and a downshift. That a positive object <tex>P</tex> has an upshift <link href="jms-004X.xml" type="local" title="Is a proposition">is a proposition</link>, so we can use our assumption that <tex>P</tex> <em>merely</em> has an upshift. That a negative object <tex>N</tex> has a downshift <link href="jms-004Z.xml" type="local" title="Is likewise a proposition">is likewise a proposition</link>, so we can use our assumption that <tex>N</tex> <em>merely</em> has a downshift.</p></block></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>9000</anchor> <rss>jms-004F.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-004F</addr>  <route>jms-004F.xml</route> <date><year>2022</year> <month>12</month> <day>26</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Preduploid</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>A deductive system <tex>\mathcal{D}</tex> is called a <em>preduploid</em> when every object <tex>A \in \mathcal{D}</tex> is <link href="jms-0045.xml" type="local" title="Polarized">polarized</link>.</p></mainmatter> </tree></backlinks> <references/></backmatter></tree>